{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622269"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:01:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:01:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16792"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16792"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.09,0.17,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9483"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76692"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9483"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62184"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5243"},{"type":"tags","id":"7631"},{"type":"tags","id":"7637"},{"type":"tags","id":"7640"},{"type":"tags","id":"7668"},{"type":"tags","id":"11073"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22414"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22635"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76692"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETaxanes are a class of chemotherapy medications that target cellular structures involved in cell division.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of taxanes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits microtubule formation","Cross-links DNA strands","Binds and stabilises microtubules","Inhibits topoisomerase II enzyme","Blocks dihydrofolate reductase"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinding and stabilising microtubules\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of action of taxanes. These drugs bind specifically to beta-tubulin subunits. The stabilisation of microtubules disrupts normal microtubule dynamics required for cell division, leading to cell cycle arrest in G2/M phase and subsequent cell death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits microtubule formation\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of vinca alkaloids, which prevent microtubule assembly rather than stabilising existing microtubules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECross-links DNA strands\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of platinum-based drugs like cisplatin, which form covalent bonds between DNA strands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits topoisomerase II enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action for drugs like etoposide, which interferes with DNA unwinding and replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks dihydrofolate reductase\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action of methotrexate, which interferes with folate metabolism and DNA synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon taxanes include paclitaxel and docetaxel, which are widely used in the treatment of various cancers including breast, ovarian, and lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Taxanes bind to beta-tubulin and stabilise microtubules, preventing cell division during mitosis.","Taxanes are used in the treatment of a variety of cancers, and include paclitaxel and docetaxel.","Taxanes are important chemotherapy agents that prevent cell division"],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62184"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16792"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62184"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T10:26:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T10:26:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9483"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76692"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},